caption: Amazing Food! Ali (Owner, Chef, Entertainer) not only prepares your meal in the kitchen which in in direct view of the diners, he has a personality that fills the room. The restaurant has a warm Mediteranean feel, decorated with all things Egyptian. I can’t recommend this restaurant enough. Don’t miss out on this experience.
Owner My Guy 💯👌🏽 Food is on Point 💯
Very good.
Dark danky place musky smell
Awesome owner/chef
It’s like stepping into someone’s home kitchen. Chef/owner is super friendly and there’s no set menu. I had the fish and it was cooked so well.

If I were fortunate enough to choose where I die, I’d like to die at Ali’s table, next to his glorious kitchen. To say this restaurant means something to me is like saying life itself means something to me. This is a sacred place. Ali is an international treasure.
Delicious food. Friendly service. Enchanting atmosphere. Wonderful!!
Phenomenal place ,first time here food is awesome))))) My friend comes over here past 18 years,I hate him )))) that he kept this place secret.....
Great but tiny little place. Owner runs the whole show himself, providing as much good conversation and humor as he does delicious food.
Featured in The New Yorker, September 2nd, 2019 - Section: Tables for Two, excellent article by David Kortava! ♥

I’ve known Ali and his restaurant for 18 years now. I save the experience for special people and special occasions. Ali is an unusual chef, very skilled and cultured and knows about all kinds of cuisines from all over the world. He is also well traveled and quite the conversationalist. The anticipation, dining, talking and savoring is all part of the unique experience that is kebab cafe. don’t expect a menu - Ali makes you what he thinks you’ll like based on his conversations with you. I’ve never had a bad experience at his place. Love it love it love it. Oh... just one thing. Remember to bring cash. My dude doesn’t do credit cards. it’s uncivilized.....:o) And do not skip the mixed appetizer plate. It’s life changing.
very nice food !!

This place is a gem. It’s a very small place with enough seating for 10-15 people. The proprietor is an excellent gentleman who cooks everything from scratch and serves it. He is also very warm and friendly. The food is delicious, full of flavors, made from ingredients that are very fresh.  Overall the experience is very personal; very different from an usual “restaurant”.  The cuisine is specifically Alexandrian, and the name “kebab cafe” doesn’t do justice - this place has so much more than just kebabs.

If there would only be one place in NYC to eat, it's Kebab Cafe. Ali, the owner, waiter and master chef is an amazing man who won't only cook an amazing meal for you, but also entertains by engaging with his guests. I hope this place stays forever.

(Translated by Google) It is not an ordinary shop. The menu was not found, but there was communication, it was full of compassion and individuality, and it had a philosophy. This is the most unique place you've ever been to. If you have time, I would recommend it.  (Original) 普通のお店では無いです。 メニューも見当たらなかったですが、そこにはコミニケーションがあり、思いやりと個性に溢れ、哲学がありました。 今まで行ったお店の中で一番ユニークな場所です。 時間に余裕があれば、おススメです。
(Translated by Google) Excellent attention  (Original) Excelente atención
We felt right at home and so welcomed! This is not just an amazing restaurant with some of the best Egyptian food, this is a whole experience!! We will be back again soon. Thank you Ali!

Ali makes you feel so as if you're right in the comfort of your on home growing up again. Get ready to taste those great delicious spices in all the food, very traditional back home food. Thank you Ali, all the best friend.
Food is so great
I love his food, been there few times he is very friendly person. I definitely recommend this place if you want a taste of Egyptian food.

You haven't had food like this yet, and that's ok. It's rare that a meal makes you feel revived. Makes you feel ready to not only tackle the rest of the week but the rest of the month. Makes you closer the person/people sitting next to you. If like your food made with lots and lots and LOTS of love...get here.
Authentic & Delicious
(Translated by Google) Delicious Egyptian meals  (Original) Deliciosas comidas egipcias

The food was absolutely great! Ali chatted with us about what we wanted and he came out with a whole roasted fish and baby goat chops that were exactly what we hoped for. Outside of home, roasted vegetable medley is somewhat of a let down, but they were great here! The hot sauce with the fried cauliflower and the falafel were very flavorful too. I'm a little sad we didn't get to try the rabbit cheeks with sweetbreads. Oddly, his choice of music was also great, so as the Germans say "there is nothing to complain about"
Just because I can

This place is the Cats pajamas. The food is always layered in authentic flavors & prepared fresh on the spot. The space is a bit rustic and quarters are a little tight,but all the better to keep the atmosphere intimate as the Head Chef Ali is the most rare & colorful ingredient in this kitchen. Such a knowledgeable & genuine person that is filled with love, & it really comes out in his cooking. Highly recommend this unique dining experience.

This place easily deserves 10 stars for the experience alone. But the food as well is second to none. At first when you walk in, it’s intimidating how small the location is, however, once you’re there, it’s a very intimate setting and the owner/chef is basically catering to just you. Everything he makes is from scratch on the spot and guaranteed to hit your taste senses in ways you’ve yet to experience. Amazing place to impress a date, a little pricey but worth it. My suggestion is get there, tell the chef “surprise me” and just roll with what he cooks. You will have no regrets guaranteed. One of the best places I’ve been to in NYC and I can’t wait to go back!
Excellent food and service. Highly recommended.

Cannot overstate the quality of food prepared by Ali. Distinct and specific, coupled with ambience in the establishment you enter another world, place and time. Any reservations you may have about eating here, consider it a terrible loss if you rob yourself of the experience. Best experience in New York (tops visit to Metropolitan Museum of Art, if you can imagine such a thing possible), we are fortunate to have this cafe in Astoria.
Chef Ali lives up to the foodie hype and more!  Incredible falafel sandwich with a side of culinary history and NYC conversation!!!
Amazing authentic food! Chef Ali makes the experience even more memorable!!!

Amazing meal, great music playing, the chef was very friendly. The place managed to be very cozy and feel like home but with some very complex and downright delicious flavors that all combined very well. We got a vegetarian platte and a cauliflower plate.
Love this place! Ali is great
A bit on the eclectic side but a must go to eatery!
We had a birthday lunch here with just us and Chef Ali and it was terrific!!  Can’t recommend it highly enough.  The food was delicious and Chef Ali was so hospitalable!!

My all-time favorite restaurant.  My daughter and I love the chef, Ali, who is a charming raconteur and a superb chef.  Ali is like Dominic DeMarco--if you don't 'get' it, the rest of the world is outside, and you are welcome to it. For those of us who do, we will sit down and enjoy the comradery of those who share a beloved delight.

Overrated, overpriced - not sure why this place gets so much play - much better Egyptian food across the street.  Arrogant, pretentious chef serving up weird concoctions he claims are Alexandrian. #ratherbland #Extremelyoverrated

One of my favorite restaurants in all of the city. Such amazing flavors and selection from a chef and his one assistant. Chef Ali (Anthony Bourdain and Jamie Oliver have had him on their shows) is a sweetheart and a charming host. He greets everyone that comes in, reads them the day's menu and prepares everyone right in front of you. Delicious Egyptian gourmet dishes. The only drawback I have about the restaurant is the space. It's super tight. It is very well decorated and the chef has his playlist on shuffle with a great variety of music. Awesome.

Chef Ali is truly a gem of a person and a cook extraordinaire! The food is always fresh (yes!) and consequently his one of a kind menu is transformed on a daily basis. I work as an architect and am accustomed to bringing friends and colleagues to see his visual creations when I am looking to impress and simply show them another side of Astoria.  I can firmly say that I've been always blown away by the beauty of his meals and their extraordinary taste. On top of it, the chef is a history aficionado so you will never be bored in his company. Highly highly recommend!!  PS if you are accustomed to take out or more generic food, this is not the place for you.
Very nice owner and home made food.
Amazing maxing amazing, so many flavors !!!!!!!!!!! Spend your money and eat good!!!

I wanted to like Kabab Cafe more than I did.  The owner is a quirky, funny nice guy.  The food wasn't bad.  Maybe I don't have enough appreciation for good food but I didn't think it was anything special.  And I thought it was expensive.  There was not a good selection of beer and wine.  The restaurant has a certain charm.  Everything is tiny and unique, a lot of character and a little bit ramshackle. It's definitely an experience.  My friend referred to the menu on the outside of the restaurant and he said that we shouldn't try to order from the menu because it hasn't been updated in years.  My friend asked about the price of an item and he scolded him, saying that this wasn't "fast food".  He tried to pressure us into ordering an appetizer.  And he was very funny and friendly but it felt a little forced.  There's a NYTimes review "Pita With a Generous Helping of Quirkiness" that's completely accurate.  We ended up order 3 beers, 1 wine, 2 chicken kebabs, and 1 appetizer sampler platter.  This was about twice as much food as we should have ordered.  The total $88.00 including tip.

Have you ever watched the movie "Jiro Dreams of Sushi", and wondered if you would ever come across one of those tiny restaurants that is owned and cooked by a man who has devoted his entire life and craft to his food and his culture?  To say this was one of the best meal ever is an understatement. With Ali, you traveled in time and space as he tells you the significance and approach to his culture and his life.  And remember. Don't call it Egyptian food. It's Alexandria food. And it's what heaven must taste like.
I'm not going over there yes

My friend and I walked in here on a Wednesday afternoon and we asked if he made a veggie plate. The "chef" flipped out and said he doesn't make the same things everyday. So we asked him what he had that day and instead of answering us, he told us to "take a seat." When we explained that we might want to take something to go, he responded that he doesn't make food to go and only "idiots" take food to go. We thought he must have been joking so we laughed and he basically kicked us out and said "have a nice day." My friend commented that he could have been a little more friendly and this guy lost it and started cursing at us and dropping F bombs. THIS GUY IS NUTS. He clearly doesn't care about having any business. SAVE YOURSELF THE TROUBLE AND EAT SOMEWHERE ELSE. Every other restaurant we've been to on that block is owned by friendly people!
So bad place , the owner treat us so bad at the end we left and we went eat in another restaurant. Going there was just waisting time . Bad experience 😡

I never been treated that bad in a restaurant as I here. The owner is just a crazy person and there place doesn't look clean at all. I came with my egyptian friends to try some arabic for and he was so unrespectful with them just because they asked about some plates that he didn't make.

My husband found this place years ago.  He always brings friends and family here when we are in town.  Everything about this place is fantastic.  Ali makes something for everyone.  Never disappointing.  Always a wonderful time.  The roasted cauliflower  with pomegranate reduction is heavenly.

I've been here on multiple occasions.  So why 3-stars?  It's a case of hit or miss.  Some visits have been spectacularly great, while others have been so-so.    It always seems to come down to Ali's mood.  He is sometimes on top of his game as a cook and an entertainer.  He sometimes is moody and the experience is not so great.
Ali is a legend.

The food here is amazing, its actually beyond amazing. Food is seasoned to perfection. It turns out the owner/chef grew up near the spices market in Alexandria, Egypt. It is a bit on a pricey side compared to other restaurants  but again there is nothing like it in the city.

I went here about 3 years ago with a friend. I saw all the bad comments and first of all it's the commentators fault most of the time. For the guy complaining about the price and there not being menus then you should of left when you found out there wasnt a menu or asked for a price when you asked what was available cause thats exactly what I did. No one forced any of you to go there and for the other complaint of the Owner charging you $5 to share a plate thats his policy. No one is forcing you guys to go to this establishment so why would you go there find out they didnt have menus and stay anyway and give the guy a bad rating for something you knew in the first place. Thats like going to McDonalds knowing they have hamburgers and giving them a bad rating because you dont like hamburgers.  Now to my experience. It was the best food I ever tasted my entire life. Like others said. There's No menu, its just whats available for the day and the Chef/Owner/Waiter tells you what he has. Ask for the price so you make sure you agree to it and not be like these fools on here ordering stuff not knowing how much it costs, lol. I ordered the Caramelized Rabbit and I forgot what my friend ordered and it was delicious. The Chef made plate with seasonings with it with ground up herbs, spices, and flowers from all over the world to make up the most tastiest thing I ever had my entire life. I was dipping my rabbit and pita bread in it and I litterally felt all my taste buds in heaven. I felt parts of my tongue that I never felt before. A sensation in my mouth that is beyond words.This was my experience and I get so angry hearing people talk bad about the owner. I love the vibe in there and he's friendly, even flirty, but hes innocent and having fun. He explained to me and my date exactly how he was going to prepare the meal and what he was going to do in it and hes a great conversationalist.  2 Dinners, an appetizer, and a tea ran me $55 after tip. Well worth it :) Best Experience I had
Excellent food. Cash only.
go with the flow and put yourself into the capable hands of the owner.
I lived in the states for fifteen years and never had Egyptian food served so creatively. The Chef is a talented artist.

Came here recommended by one of my colleagues. This foodie restaurant is definitely a hole in the wall worth travelling to. Located in the Astoria part of Queens, you will find Ali's Kebab Cafe which servers a mixture of Egyptian and African fare. When you enter the establishment, you are greeted by Ali, he is the owner, chef, and the only staff. There is no menu, but Ali will tell you what is available for the day. You can the meat or fish, and he will decide how he will cook and serve it. Their choices are not for the weak stomach so be prepared. Our dinner consisted of lamb cheeks, lamb thyroid, goat shank, and rabbit. All dishes were either sauteed or stewed in Egyptian spices. I would say this has got to be one of the most amazing Egyptian food I have ever tasted this side of the hemisphere and I definitely recommend.

He told my boyfriend that he would charge him $5 to share a plate because he had wanted me to try it with him because it was his extra credit assignment. I didn't want to but he did, so the guy was not joking when he said we had to pay $5 extra for a fork and and extra napkin. Which is cheap and obsered. We decided to take to go after my boyfriend said no just that would be fine. After 20 minutes it was ready, he charged him $14 for it when the menu said $9. After he agreed he would just give one plate, Instead he still charged $5 more. Did not like it he didn't come to us when we entered yet for two white couples he went right to them and ask how they were and what he would recommend. Found it very rude and how he would charge us $5 for a fork and napkin. Food was not that good. I had just ate the bread that came with it, pretty plain.

Great atmosphere, tiny and slightly dingy place.  Smells heavenly. Everybody is on top of each other. I brought a chef friend for what I expected to be a an unusual and tasty meal for his birthday. Some of the food was fantastic, but some mediocre at best. All seemed fresh except the packaged pita. Owner/chef/waiter appears very friendly. No menu. Full of young diners. We had a couple of beers, 3 appetizers and a main dish. I was stunned to find out at the end that we owed $95!!! If there was a menu or any posted prices, we would have left. At half the price I would have considered it an experience. At $100 it was a total ripoff that left us with a bitter taste. Too bad - I was really looking forward eating there. PS by looking at the young coupes there, I can not believe that the same prices are charged for everyone.
Whimsical, delicious, fresh, creative, perfectly seasoned eats served directly from the chef in a tiny shop on Steinway. Everyone else stay away. This place is MINE
Delicious

Its been a couple years since I ate here, but I still remember it fondly.  Freakin delicious.  Super tiny.  But inside it feels like you are in a tiny restaurant in Egypt.  The slightly dirty, loud boisterous laughing, art painted on the walls, everyone is family, ask for the chef's favorite and get something incredible off menu, but be prepared that an un-gloved finger may taste your dish before you do.  It feels authentic and down to earth.  For those of us who have traveled in rugged and poor countries, this place is amazing.  If you are a picky and classy kind of foodie, you might not like it.
One of the best meals I've had. Lamb cheeks and sweetbreads. Had second thoughts when seeing how small, but glad I went in.  really is like eating in someone's kitchen. Loved it!

Don't be fooled by the generic name and the tiny storefront, Kabab Cafe has absolutely amazing food. There is a menu, but you can safely ignore it -  the chef recommends dishes and just starts bringing out food. The ambiance is like sitting in someone's kitchen hearing them tell family stories while making your meal. The place is absolutely tiny, but you can eat without hurry.
Unparalleled, sweetbreads and lamb cheek were amazing

The chef prepares delicious food. The prices are not outrageous. It is Middle Eastern food. I liked the falafel and hummous. I do not particularly like lamb but the fish was delicious and very fresh. service was excellent.

What a place! This was probably the best falafel I have ever tasted! The owner is a wonderful man, the open kitchen, the atmosphere, they all work together to make one fantastic meal. We also had some steak, some liver, they were all quite wonderful. Highly highly recommended!

I recently tried out Kabab Cafe with a group of friends. To put it plainly, we had a blast. The place is tiny, but we managed to all squeeze into a corner. The decor is whimsical and homey. Chef Ali asked us what we felt like eating and made some recommendations. We began with the appetizer platter of hummous, falafel, and baba ganouj with a touch of Egyptian hocus-pocus, followed by roasted cauliflower in a pomegranate reduction and lamb "cheeks" with an egg stirred in. We also shared a melt-in-your-mouth lamb shank (shank you very much) with vegetables as well as chicken and vegetables and a broiled fish with citrus. The flavors were complex without being pretentious. Portions are large; we ended up spending about $25/person (which felt like a pretty good deal for 4 hours of eating) and left feeling stuffed and happy.   This is a unique restaurant--while Astoria is known for cheap (if not necessarily amazing) Middle Eastern food, Kabab Cafe is a bit pricey for everyday meals but an excellent value for a special occasion. It doesn't do takeout, has endless possibilities but no menu, and you can BYOB (bring your own water while you're at it--they only serve bottled water). The staff consists only of Ali and his helper, and he cooks right in the middle of the room so you can watch everything while engaging in lively banter. He'll talk to you about food, Egypt, politics, whatever, and corny jokes are par for the course. He plays an unconventional assortment of music from the Soggy Bottom Boys to Natacha Atlas. The bottom line: If you're looking for an unforgettable dining experience, this is it!

Excellently prepared food of the style of Alexandria, Egypt.  The food is a bit expensive, though.  The owner, Ali, is awesome and really the highlight of the restaurant.  By the way, this is a tiny place, way too small to support large groups.
